        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Isn't the paste itself (new text, scrolling with newlines) ample visual indicator of progress?\n\nTrue, but if we can show a visual aid then of course we should (and will, eventually, more often). (Also IIRC, there was a potential need to collect pasted text without immediately updating the buffer.)\n\nShell also has a \"throbber\" (example: `:!yes`) where we *do* still buffer to avoid flooding the UI.\n\nMeanwhile, for `vim.paste` we can workaround this by using 'statusline' (or just remove it).\n\n```diff\ndiff --git a/runtime/lua/vim/_core/editor.lua b/runtime/lua/vim/_core/editor.lua\nindex 8c49dc8bd2d0..b71a590f2597 100644\n--- a/runtime/lua/vim/_core/editor.lua\n+++ b/runtime/lua/vim/_core/editor.lua\n@@ -234,7 +234,9 @@ do\n       tick = tick + 1\n       -- Use :echo because Lua print('') is a no-op, and we want to clear the\n       -- message when there are zero dots.\n-      vim.api.nvim_command(('echo \"%s\"'):format(dots))\n+      -- vim.api.nvim_command(('echo \"%s\"'):format(dots))\n+      -- vim.cmd'let &busy=!&busy | redrawstatus'\n+      vim.cmd('let &l:statusline=\"'..dots..'\" | redrawstatus')\n     end\n     if startpos == nil then\n       startpos = vim.fn.getpos(\"'[\")\n```\n",
